  <static seed="1603" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations28.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{1}{y-5}-\frac{3}{y+6}}={-\frac{7}{y^{2}+y-30}}  }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="31" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{14\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To clear fractions in an equation, multiply each side of the equation by a common denominator. For this problem, a common denominator is <m>{\left(y-5\right)\mathopen{}\left(y+6\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  {\frac{1}{y-5}-\frac{3}{y+6}} \amp = {-\frac{7}{y^{2}+y-30}} \\
  {\frac{1}{y-5}-\frac{3}{y+6}} \amp = {-\frac{7}{\left(y-5\right)\mathopen{}\left(y+6\right)}} \\
  {\frac{1}{y-5}\mathopen{}\left(y-5\right)\mathopen{}\left(y+6\right)-\frac{3}{y+6}\mathopen{}\left(y-5\right)\mathopen{}\left(y+6\right)} \amp = {-\frac{7}{\left(y-5\right)\mathopen{}\left(y+6\right)}\mathopen{}\left(y-5\right)\mathopen{}\left(y+6\right)} \\
  {y+6-3\mathopen{}\left(y-5\right)} \amp = {-7} \\
  {y+6-3y+15} \amp = {-7} \\
  {-2y+21} \amp = {-7} \\
  {-2y} \amp = -28 \\
  \frac{-2 y}{-2} \amp = \frac{-28}{-2} \\
  y \amp = 14
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. In the original equation, both denominators cannot be <m>0</m>. We set them to <m>0</m>, so we can find out what values to exclude from the solution set.</p>
<p>For this example, it<rsq/>s easy to see we must exclude <m>5</m> and <m>-6</m> from the solution set. These values are not in the solution set we got, so the final solution is <m>y=14</m>.</p>
</solution>
